TOPICS COVERED (LINEAR REGRESSION – IMPLEMENTATION & MODEL EVALUATION)
Introduction to Linear Regression

The training session began with an in-depth study of Linear Regression, one of the simplest and most commonly used supervised Machine Learning algorithms. Learned that Linear Regression is used to predict continuous numerical values by establishing a linear relationship between one or more independent variables (features) and a dependent variable (target).

The trainer explained that Linear Regression helps estimate future values based on historical data and is widely used in forecasting and predictive analytics.

Examples discussed included:

House Price Prediction
Salary Prediction
Sales Forecasting
Student Marks Prediction
Temperature Prediction
Understanding the Concept of Regression

Studied how regression analysis identifies the relationship between variables.

Learned the basic components of a regression model:

Independent Variable (Feature)
Dependent Variable (Target)
Regression Line
Slope (Coefficient)
Intercept

Discussed how the regression line represents the best fit through the given data points and minimizes prediction errors.

Simple Linear Regression

Received an introduction to Simple Linear Regression, where only one independent variable is used to predict the target variable.

Worked with examples such as:

Experience vs Salary
Study Hours vs Marks
House Size vs House Price

Learned the mathematical equation:

Y = mX + c

Where:

Y = Predicted Output
X = Input Feature
m = Slope (Coefficient)
c = Intercept

Understood how the model calculates the best-fit line using training data.

Multiple Linear Regression

Studied Multiple Linear Regression, where multiple independent variables are used to predict a single target variable.

Examples included:

House Price Prediction using Area, Number of Rooms, and Location
Student Performance Prediction using Attendance, Study Hours, and Previous Scores

Learned that multiple features often improve prediction accuracy compared to a single feature.

